117 Sec. 6. (NEW) (Effective October 1, 2026) (a) Except as provided in
118 subsection (b) of section 2 of this act, a deployer who has deployed an
119 automated employment-related decision process to make, or be a
120 substantial factor in making, an employment-related decision
121 concerning an applicant for employment or employee in the state shall,
122 if such employment-related decision is adverse to such applicant or
123 employee, provide to such applicant or employee:
124 (1) A high-level statement disclosing the principal reason or reasons
125 for such adverse employment-related decision, including, but not
126 limited to, (A) the degree to which, and manner in which, the automated
127 employment-related decision process contributed to such adverse
128 employment-related decision, (B) the type of data that were processed
129 by such automated employment-related decision process in making, or
130 as a substantial factor in making, such adverse employment-related
131 decision, and (C) the source of the data described in subparagraph (B)
132 of this subdivision;
LCO No. 2788 5 of 24

Raised Bill No. 435
133 (2) An opportunity to (A) examine the data the automated
134 employment-related decision process processed in making, or as a
135 substantial factor in making, such adverse employment-related
136 decision, (B) correct any incorrect data described in subparagraph (A) of
137 this subdivision, and (C) appeal such adverse employment-related
138 decision if such adverse employment-related decision is based upon any
139 incorrect data described in subparagraph (A) of this subdivision. Such
140 appeal shall allow for human review; and
141 (3) Upon request by such applicant or employee, or such applicant or
142 employee's representative, a copy of the most recent bias audit required
143 pursuant to section 8 of this act.
144 (b) A deployer who is required to provide a high-level statement to
145 an applicant for employment or employee in the state pursuant to
146 subdivision (1) of subsection (a) of this section shall provide such
147 statement:
148 (1) Directly to such applicant or employee;
149 (2) In plain language;
150 (3) In all languages in which such deployer, in the ordinary course of
151 such deployer's business, provides contracts, disclaimers, sales
152 announcements and other information to persons in the state; and
153 (4) In a format that is accessible to individuals with disabilities.
154 Sec. 7. (NEW) (Effective October 1, 2026) (a) For the purposes of this
155 section "human review" means a review conducted by a qualified
156 individual who (1) has the authority to make or change an employment-
157 related decision, (2) understands the capabilities, limitations and risks
158 of the automated employment-related decision process, including, but
159 not limited to, patterns of bias, disparate impact and data quality issues,
160 and (3) does not rely solely on the content, decision, prediction or
161 recommendation generated by the automated employment-related
LCO No. 2788 6 of 24

Raised Bill No. 435
162 decision process in making a final or determinative employment-related
163 decision.
164 (b) (1) A deployer who has deployed an automated employment-
165 related decision process in making, or as a substantial factor in making,
166 an employment-related decision concerning an applicant for
167 employment or employee in the state shall implement human review
168 over such automated employment-related decision process by
169 providing for review of the content, decisions, predictions or
170 recommendations generated by the automated employment-related
171 decision process and any other information relevant to such content,
172 decision, prediction or recommendation in order to confirm the
173 accuracy of data processed by such automated employment-related
174 decision process and, when appropriate, modify or veto any such
175 content, decision, prediction or recommendation generated by such
176 automated decision-making process prior to any adverse employment-
177 related decision.
178 (2) A deployer shall (A) establish procedures necessary to pause,
179 correct or reverse erroneous or harmful content, decision, prediction or
180 recommendation generated by an automated employment-related
181 decision process, and (B) establish and maintain logs listing all human
182 review reports and any intervention taken by an individual conducting
183 such human review.
184 (c) No automated employment-related decision process shall be used
185 by a deployer in making a final or determinative employment-related
186 decision without human review over such final or determinative
187 employment-related decision.
188 Sec. 8. (NEW) (Effective October 1, 2026) (a) (1) Prior to deploying an
189 automated employment-related decision process, and annually
190 thereafter, a deployer shall contract with an independent auditor to
191 complete a bias audit. Such bias audit shall be done not later than one
192 year prior to the date the deployer intends to deploy such automated
LCO No. 2788 7 of 24

Raised Bill No. 435
193 employment-related decision process.
194 (2) Each bias audit conducted pursuant to this subsection shall:
195 (A) Evaluate the automated employment-related decision process
196 performance and error rates across relevant subgroups;
197 (B) Assess disparate impact caused by the automated employment-
198 related decision process against protected classes;
199 (C) Examine the sources of data processed by the automated
200 employment-related decision process and quality of content, decisions,
201 predictions or recommendations generated by the automated
202 employment-related decision process;
203 (D) Evaluate the effects of any thresholds, scoring or ranking criteria
204 utilized by the automated employment-related decision process; and
205 (E) Test for less discriminatory alternatives or adjustments to such
206 automated employment-related decision process.
207 (3) No deployer shall contract with an independent auditor who (A)
208 has a financial or operational interest in the deployer or developer of the
209 automated employment-related decision process, or (B) has not been
210 approved by the Labor Commissioner pursuant to subsection (b) of this
211 section.
212 (b) The Labor Commissioner shall establish and implement an
213 approval process of independent auditors to conduct bias audits
214 pursuant to subsection (a) of this section and shall maintain a registry of
215 independent auditors approved by such process.
216 (c) Not later than thirty days after completing a bias audit pursuant
217 to subsection (a) of this section, the deployer shall (1) in a form and
218 manner prescribed by the Labor Commissioner, file a bias audit report
219 and a plain-language summary of such report with the commissioner,
220 and (2) publish a plain-language summary of such audit report on the
LCO No. 2788 8 of 24

Raised Bill No. 435
221 deployer's Internet web site in a conspicuous place accessible to
222 applicants for employment and employees. Such summary shall include
223 (A) the methodology used in such bias audit, (B) the key findings and
224 identified risks found by such bias audit, and (C) any corrective actions
225 taken by the deployer.
226 (d) No automated employment-related decision process shall be
227 deployed or continue to be deployed by a deployer if the most recent
228 bias audit conducted pursuant to subsection (a) of this section identified
229 any disparate impact caused by such automated employment-related
230 decision process, except where the deployer can demonstrate (1) a
231 business necessity, (2) such deployer has implemented corrective
232 actions approved by the Labor Commissioner, and (3) that either (A) no
233 less discriminatory alternative is available, or (B) a less discriminatory
234 alternative has been implemented by the deployer.
235 (e) Each deployer shall maintain records relating to bias audits
236 required pursuant to subsection (a) of this section for a period of not less
237 than five years and shall make such records available to the Labor
238 Commissioner upon request.
239 (f) The Labor Commissioner may adopt regulations, in accordance
240 with the provisions of chapter 54 of the general statutes, necessary to
241 carry out the purposes of this section, including, but not limited to,
242 establishing minimum qualifications for independent auditors and
243 methodologic requirements for bias audits required pursuant to
244 subsection (a) of this section.
245 Sec. 9. (NEW) (Effective October 1, 2026) No employer, deployer,
246 developer, labor organization or any other person shall discharge or in
247 any manner discriminate or retaliate against, any applicant for
248 employment or employee because such applicant or employee:
249 (1) Filed a complaint, provided information or otherwise assisted in
250 an investigation or proceeding concerning any alleged violation of
251 sections 3 to 8 of this act;
LCO No. 2788 9 of 24

Raised Bill No. 435
252 (2) Objected to or refused to participate in any activity that such
253 applicant or employee reasonably believed to be in violation of sections
254 3 to 8 of this act; or
255 (3) Exercised any rights granted under the provisions of sections 3 to
256 8 of this act.
257 Sec. 10. (NEW) (Effective October 1, 2026) (a) No provision of sections
258 2 to 8, inclusive, of this act shall be construed to require any person to
259 disclose any information that is a trade secret or otherwise protected
260 from disclosure under state or federal law.
261 (b) If a person withholds any information under subsection (a) of this
262 section, the person shall send a notice to the person from whom such
263 information is being withheld. Such notice shall disclose (1) that such
264 person is withholding such information, and (2) the basis for such
265 person's decision to withhold such information.
266 Sec. 11. (NEW) (Effective October 1, 2026) Any violation of the
267 provisions of sections 3 to 8, inclusive, of this act shall constitute an
268 unfair or deceptive trade practice for the purposes of subsection (a) of
269 section 42-110b of the general statutes and shall be enforced solely by
270 the Attorney General. The provisions of section 42-110g of the general
271 statutes shall not apply to any such violation.
272 Sec. 12. (NEW) (Effective October 1, 2026) An employee aggrieved by
273 a violation of sections 3 to 9, inclusive, of this act may bring a civil action
274 in the Superior Court to recover damages and equitable relief together
275 with costs and reasonable attorney's fees.
276 Sec. 13. (NEW) (Effective October 1, 2026) Where an applicant for
277 employment or employee is represented by an employee organization,
278 a deployer shall (1) provide written notice prior to any testing,
279 deployment or material modification of an automated employment-
280 related decision process, and (2) engage in good faith bargaining with
281 such employee organization regarding the purpose, scope and
