282 anticipated impacts of such automated employment-related decision
283 process.
284 Sec. 14. (NEW) (Effective October 1, 2026) (a) As used in this section,
285 section 17 of this act and sections 5-271 of the general statutes, as
286 amended by this act, and 7-468 of the general statutes, as amended by
287 this act, "artificial intelligence technology" means a computer system,
288 application or other product that uses or incorporates one or more forms
289 of artificial intelligence.
290 (b) (1) No state agency, or any entity acting on behalf of a state
291 agency, shall, directly or indirectly, utilize or apply any artificial
292 intelligence technology in performing any function that (A) is related to
293 the delivery of any public assistance benefit to individuals in the state
294 by such agency, or (B) will have a material impact on the rights, civil
295 liberties, safety or welfare of individuals in the state, unless such
296 utilization or application is specifically authorized by law.
297 (2) No state agency shall authorize any procurement, purchase or
298 acquisition of any artificial intelligence technology, except where the use
299 of such system is specifically authorized by law.
300 (3) If a state agency is authorized to procure, purchase or acquire an
301 artificial intelligence technology, the state agency shall contract with an
302 independent auditor to complete a bias audit pursuant to subsection (a)
303 of section 8 of this act.
304 (c) Any bias audit completed pursuant to subdivision (3) of
305 subsection (b) of this section shall be submitted to the Commissioner of
306 Administrative Services, in a form and manner prescribed by the
307 commissioner, and posted on the agency's Internet web site not later
308 than sixty days prior to deployment of such artificial intelligence
309 technology. Any agency may redact any data in such impact statement
310 to remove personally identifiable information of any individual.
