480 pregnancy; (F) to discriminate against an employee or person seeking
481 employment on the basis of her pregnancy in the terms or conditions of
482 her employment; (G) to fail or refuse to make a reasonable
483 accommodation for an employee or person seeking employment due to
484 her pregnancy, unless the employer can demonstrate that such
485 accommodation would impose an undue hardship on such employer;
486 (H) to deny employment opportunities to an employee or person
487 seeking employment if such denial is due to the employee's request for
488 a reasonable accommodation due to her pregnancy; (I) to force an
489 employee or person seeking employment affected by pregnancy to
490 accept a reasonable accommodation if such employee or person seeking
491 employment (i) does not have a known limitation related to her
492 pregnancy, or (ii) does not require a reasonable accommodation to
493 perform the essential duties related to her employment; (J) to require an
494 employee to take a leave of absence if a reasonable accommodation can
495 be provided in lieu of such leave; and (K) to retaliate against an
496 employee in the terms, conditions or privileges of her employment
497 based upon such employee's request for a reasonable accommodation.
498 [;]
499 (8) For an employer, by the employer or the employer's agent, for an
500 employment agency, by itself or its agent, or for any labor organization,
LCO No. 2788 17 of 24

Raised Bill No. 435
501 by itself or its agent, to harass any employee, person seeking
502 employment or member on the basis of sex or gender identity or
503 expression. If an employer takes immediate corrective action in
504 response to an employee's claim of sexual harassment, such corrective
505 action shall not modify the conditions of employment of the employee
506 making the claim of sexual harassment unless such employee agrees, in
507 writing, to any modification in the conditions of employment.
508 "Corrective action" taken by an employer, includes, but is not limited to,
509 employee relocation, assigning an employee to a different work
510 schedule or other substantive changes to an employee's terms and
511 conditions of employment. Notwithstanding an employer's failure to
512 obtain a written agreement from an employee concerning a modification
513 in the conditions of employment, the commission may find that
514 corrective action taken by an employer was reasonable and not of
515 detriment to the complainant based on the evidence presented to the
516 commission by the complainant and respondent. As used in this
517 subdivision, "sexual harassment" means any unwelcome sexual
518 advances or requests for sexual favors or any conduct of a sexual nature
519 when (A) submission to such conduct is made either explicitly or
520 implicitly a term or condition of an individual's employment, (B)
521 submission to or rejection of such conduct by an individual is used as
522 the basis for employment decisions affecting such individual, or (C)
523 such conduct has the purpose or effect of substantially interfering with
524 an individual's work performance or creating an intimidating, hostile or
525 offensive working environment. [;]
526 (9) For an employer, by the employer or the employer's agent, for an
527 employment agency, by itself or its agent, or for any labor organization,
528 by itself or its agent, to request or require information from an
529 employee, person seeking employment or member relating to the
530 individual's child-bearing age or plans, pregnancy, function of the
531 individual's reproductive system, use of birth control methods, or the
532 individual's familial responsibilities, unless such information is directly
533 related to a bona fide occupational qualification or need, provided an
LCO No. 2788 18 of 24

Raised Bill No. 435
534 employer, through a physician may request from an employee any such
535 information which is directly related to workplace exposure to
536 substances which may cause birth defects or constitute a hazard to an
537 individual's reproductive system or to a fetus if the employer first
538 informs the employee of the hazards involved in exposure to such
539 substances. [;]
540 (10) For an employer, by the employer or the employer's agent, after
541 informing an employee, pursuant to subdivision (9) of this subsection,
542 of a workplace exposure to substances which may cause birth defects or
543 constitute a hazard to an employee's reproductive system or to a fetus,
544 to fail or refuse, upon the employee's request, to take reasonable
545 measures to protect the employee from the exposure or hazard
546 identified, or to fail or refuse to inform the employee that the measures
547 taken may be the subject of a complaint filed under the provisions of
548 this chapter. Nothing in this subdivision is intended to prohibit an
549 employer from taking reasonable measures to protect an employee from
550 exposure to such substances. For the purpose of this subdivision,
551 "reasonable measures" are those measures which are consistent with
552 business necessity and are least disruptive of the terms and conditions
553 of the employee's employment. [;]
554 (11) For an employer, by the employer or the employer's agent, for an
555 employment agency, by itself or its agent, or for any labor organization,
556 by itself or its agent: (A) To request or require genetic information from
557 an employee, person seeking employment or member, or (B) to
558 discharge, expel or otherwise discriminate against any person on the
559 basis of genetic information. For the purpose of this subdivision,
560 "genetic information" means the information about genes, gene
561 products or inherited characteristics that may derive from an individual
562 or a family member. [;]
563 (12) For an employer, by the employer or the employer's agent, to
564 request or require a prospective employee's age, date of birth, dates of
565 attendance at or date of graduation from an educational institution on
LCO No. 2788 19 of 24

Raised Bill No. 435
566 an initial employment application, provided the provisions of this
567 subdivision shall not apply to any employer requesting or requiring
568 such information (A) based on a bona fide occupational qualification or
569 need, or (B) when such information is required to comply with any
570 provision of state or federal law. [; and]
571 (13) (A) For an employer or the employer's agent to deny an employee
572 a reasonable leave of absence in order to: (i) Seek attention for injuries
573 caused by domestic violence, sexual assault or trafficking in persons,
574 including for a child who is a victim of domestic violence, sexual assault
575 or trafficking in persons, provided the employee is not the perpetrator
576 of any act of domestic violence, sexual assault or trafficking in persons
577 committed against a child; (ii) obtain services including safety planning
578 from a domestic violence agency or rape crisis center, as those terms are
579 defined in section 52-146k, as a result of domestic violence, sexual
580 assault or trafficking in persons; (iii) obtain psychological counseling
581 related to an incident or incidents of domestic violence, sexual assault
582 or trafficking in persons, including for a child who is a victim of
583 domestic violence, sexual assault or trafficking in persons, provided the
584 employee is not the perpetrator of any act of domestic violence, sexual
585 assault or trafficking in persons committed against a child; (iv) take
586 other actions to increase safety from future incidents of domestic
587 violence, sexual assault or trafficking in persons, including temporary
588 or permanent relocation; or (v) obtain legal services, assisting in the
589 prosecution of the offense, or otherwise participate in legal proceedings
590 in relation to the incident or incidents of domestic violence, sexual
591 assault or trafficking in persons.
592 (B) An employee who is absent from work in accordance with the
593 provisions of subparagraph (A) of this subdivision shall, within a
594 reasonable time after the absence, provide a certification to the employer
595 when requested by the employer. Such certification shall be in the form
596 of: (i) A police report indicating that the employee or the employee's
597 child was a victim of domestic violence, sexual assault or trafficking in
598 persons; (ii) a court order protecting or separating the employee or
LCO No. 2788 20 of 24

Raised Bill No. 435
599 employee's child from the perpetrator of an act of domestic violence,
600 sexual assault or trafficking in persons; (iii) other evidence from the
601 court or prosecuting attorney that the employee appeared in court; or
602 (iv) documentation from a medical professional, including a domestic
603 violence counselor or sexual assault counselor, as those terms are
604 defined in section 52-146k, or other health care provider, that the
605 employee or the employee's child was receiving services, counseling or
606 treatment for physical or mental injuries or abuse resulting in
607 victimization from an act of domestic violence, sexual assault or
608 trafficking in persons.
609 (C) Where an employee has a physical or mental disability resulting
610 from an incident or series of incidents of domestic violence, sexual
611 assault or trafficking in persons, such employee shall be treated in the
612 same manner as an employee with any other disability.
613 (D) To the extent permitted by law, employers shall maintain the
614 confidentiality of any information regarding an employee's status as a
615 victim of domestic violence, sexual assault or trafficking in persons.
616 (c) (1) The provisions of this section concerning age shall not apply
617 to: (A) The termination of employment of any person with a contract of
618 unlimited tenure at an independent institution of higher education who
619 is mandatorily retired, on or before July 1, 1993, after having attained
620 the age of seventy; (B) the termination of employment of any person
621 who has attained the age of sixty-five and who, for the two years
622 immediately preceding such termination, is employed in a bona fide
623 executive or a high policy-making position, if such person is entitled to
624 an immediate nonforfeitable annual retirement benefit under a pension,
625 profit-sharing, savings or deferred compensation plan, or any
626 combination of such plans, from such person's employer, which equals,
627 in aggregate, at least forty-four thousand dollars; (C) the termination of
628 employment of persons in occupations, including police work and fire-
629 fighting, in which age is a bona fide occupational qualification; (D) the
630 operation of any bona fide apprenticeship system or plan; or (E) the
LCO No. 2788 21 of 24

Raised Bill No. 435
631 observance of the terms of a bona fide seniority system or any bona fide
632 employee benefit plan for retirement, pensions or insurance which is not
633 adopted for the purpose of evading said provisions, except that no such
634 plan may excuse the failure to hire any individual and no such system
635 or plan may require or permit the termination of employment on the
636 basis of age. No such plan which covers less than twenty employees may
637 reduce the group hospital, surgical or medical insurance coverage
638 provided under the plan to any employee who has reached the age of
639 sixty-five and is eligible for Medicare benefits or any employee's spouse
640 who has reached age sixty-five and is eligible for Medicare benefits
641 except to the extent such coverage is provided by Medicare. The terms
642 of any such plan which covers twenty or more employees shall entitle
643 any employee who has attained the age of sixty-five and any employee's
644 spouse who has attained the age of sixty-five to group hospital, surgical
645 or medical insurance coverage under the same conditions as any
646 covered employee or spouse who is under the age of sixty-five.
647 (2) No employee retirement or pension plan may exclude any
648 employee from membership in such plan or cease or reduce the
649 employee's benefit accruals or allocations under such plan on the basis
650 of age. The provisions of this subdivision shall be applicable to plan
651 years beginning on or after January 1, 1988, except that for any
652 collectively bargained plan this subdivision shall be applicable on the
653 earlier of (A) January 1, 1990, or (B) the later of (i) the expiration date of
654 the collective bargaining agreement, or (ii) January 1, 1988.
655 (3) The provisions of this section concerning age shall not prohibit an
656 employer from requiring medical examinations for employees for the
657 purpose of determining such employees' physical qualification for
658 continued employment.
659 (4) Any employee who continues employment beyond the normal
660 retirement age in the applicable retirement or pension plan shall give
661 notice of intent to retire, in writing, to such employee's employer not
662 less than thirty days prior to the date of such retirement.
LCO No. 2788 22 of 24

Raised Bill No. 435
663 (d) (1) An employer shall provide written notice of the right to be free
664 from discrimination in relation to pregnancy, childbirth and related
665 conditions, including the right to a reasonable accommodation to the
666 known limitations related to pregnancy pursuant to subdivision (7) of
667 subsection (b) of this section to: (A) New employees at the
668 commencement of employment; (B) existing employees within one
669 hundred twenty days of October 1, 2017; and (C) any employee who
670 notifies the employer of her pregnancy within ten days of such
671 notification. An employer may comply with the provisions of this
672 section by displaying a poster in a conspicuous place, accessible to
673 employees, at the employer's place of business that contains the
674 information required by this section in both English and Spanish. The
675 Labor Commissioner may adopt regulations, in accordance with
676 chapter 54, to establish additional requirements concerning the means
677 by which employers shall provide such notice.
678 (2) The Commission on Human Rights and Opportunities shall
679 develop courses of instruction and conduct ongoing public education
680 efforts as necessary to inform employers, employees, employment
681 agencies and persons seeking employment about their rights and
682 responsibilities under this section.
